  "A pulling force transmitted through a rope, string, or cable between objects": "",
  "The perpendicular contact force that a surface exerts on a resting object": "",
  "The gravitational force that pulls all objects toward the center of Earth": "",
  "Friction is a contact force that opposes the relative motion (or attempted motion) between two surfaces in contact. It can be static (preventing motion) or kinetic (opposing ongoing sliding). Friction depends on the surfaces and the normal force.": "",
  "What does the term 'static friction' mean?": "",
  "The friction force that acts on an object that is currently sliding": "",
  "The friction force that prevents an object from starting to move": "",
  "The normal force that acts perpendicular to the surface of contact": "",
  "The tension force in a rope when it is holding an object at rest": "",
  "Static friction is the friction force that acts on a stationary object to prevent it from starting to move. It adjusts its magnitude up to a maximum value (fₛ,max = μₛN). Once the applied force exceeds this maximum, the object begins to slide.": "",
  "What does the term 'kinetic friction' mean?": "",
  "The friction that acts on an object that is already sliding across a surface": "",
  "The friction that prevents a stationary object from beginning to move": "",
  "The gravitational force pulling an object along a surface toward Earth": "",
  "The tension force that keeps an object attached to a rope or cable": "",
  "Kinetic friction acts on a moving (sliding) object and opposes the direction of motion. It has a constant value for given surfaces: fₖ = μₖN. Kinetic friction is always less than or equal to the maximum static friction.": "",
